    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-05-26T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-05-26T00:00:00-05:00" n="95"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d95">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">874.00/482</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the Chief of the Division of Near Eastern
                        Affairs</hi> (<hi rend="italic">Murray</hi>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-05-26">May 26,
                            1934</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>I inquired of Mr. Hackworth<note n="1" xml:id="d95fn1">Green H. Hackworth, Legal
                        Adviser.</note> what bearing, if any, in his opinion the bloodless <hi
                        rend="italic">coup d’état</hi> in Bulgaria of May 19, 1934, might have on
                    the question of recognition. Mr. Hackworth stated that he considered that the
                    question of recognition did not arise as there had been no change either in
                    régime or in the head of the State; while it was true that the cabinet change
                    which resulted from the <hi rend="italic">coup d’état</hi> was brought about by
                    means which were non-parliamentary in character <pb facs="0202" n="102"
                        xml:id="pg_102"/> the important element to be considered in this connection
                    was that the King had immediately, by official decree, given his sanction to the
                    change.</p>
                <p>The foregoing views expressed by Mr. Hackworth confirm in every respect my own
                    conclusions in the matter.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Wallace Murray</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
